  <trial_identification>
    <studytitle>Vein Pulsation Study trial in Glaucoma</studytitle>
    <scientifictitle>Improving the management of glaucoma through better prediction of susceptible patients and improved understanding of surgical success</scientifictitle>
    <utrn />
    <trialacronym>VPSG</trialacronym>
  </trial_identification>
  <conditions>
    <healthcondition>Glaucoma</healthcondition>
    <conditioncode>
      <conditioncode1>Eye</conditioncode1>
      <conditioncode2>Diseases / disorders of the eye</conditioncode2>
    </conditioncode>
  </conditions>
  <interventions>
    <interventions>The optic nerve venous pulsation will be measured using an Ophthalmodynamometer which allows the ocular force to be measured at the same time that the back of the eye is being viewed by the examiner.  The ophthalmodynamometer  allows measurement of the force required to cause the vein and artery within the nerve to pulsate. The study will run for 5 years.</interventions>
    <comparator>Force required to collapse retinal veins and arteries converted to perfusion pressure quotient.</comparator>
    <control>Uncontrolled</control>
    <interventioncode>Diagnosis / Prognosis</interventioncode>
  </interventions>
  <outcomes>
    <primaryOutcome>
      <outcome>Detection of glaucoma progression by visual field and optic disk photography</outcome>
      <timepoint>5 years</timepoint>
    </primaryOutcome>
    <secondaryOutcome>
      <outcome>Detection of glaucoma progression by visual field and optic disk photography</outcome>
      <timepoint>1 year</timepoint>
    </secondaryOutcome>
    <secondaryOutcome>
      <outcome>Detection of glaucoma progression by visual field and optic disk photography</outcome>
      <timepoint>3 years</timepoint>
    </secondaryOutcome>
  </outcomes>
  <eligibility>
